More supporting cast: translate, word-count, head, and tail.

Translate, the t-r command, replaces or deletes individual characters. It is not a full search-and-replace; for that you use sed. Translate works one character at a time, mapping one set of characters to another. So it can upper-case a line by mapping the lowercase range to the uppercase range, delete specific characters like commas and exclamation marks with the dash d flag, or squeeze runs of repeated characters down to one with the dash s flag, which is handy for collapsing multiple spaces. One quirk: translate only reads from standard input, so you always pipe into it rather than handing it a filename.

Word-count, spelled w-c, counts things. Dash l counts lines, and that is the one you will use perhaps nine times out of ten, for questions like how many users are in the password file or how many entries are in a directory. Dash w counts words, dash c counts bytes, and dash m counts characters, which differs from bytes once you have non-english text.

Finally, head and tail show you the first or last lines of their input, ten by default, adjustable with the dash n flag. Tail has a couple of extra tricks: give it dash n with a plus sign and a number, and it prints from that line onwards rather than from the end. And its most famous feature is the dash f flag, follow mode, which keeps printing new lines as they are appended; it is the standard way to watch a log file in real time, and you press control-c to stop. With those, you have met the whole small-tool toolkit, and it is time to start combining them.
